entry.title: Astrotricha ledifolia s.s.
entry.content: Just getting started with buds but plants observed in the area have more leaves than last year.

entry.title: Boronia anemonifolia subsp. anemonifolia
entry.content: This white with pink tinged flowering bush is typical of what is occurring this spring.

entry.title: Euryomyrtus ramosissima subsp. ramosissima
entry.content: Great flowering after good winter rains.

entry.title: Boronia anemonifolia subsp. anemonifolia
entry.content: This very pink flowering plant is one amongst the many white/pinkish flowering specimens.

entry.title: Prostanthera decussata
entry.content: First flowers for the season - many buds.

entry.title: Pomaderris elliptica var. elliptica
entry.content: I waited and waited for this to flower and missed it by that much.

entry.title: Leionema lamprophyllum subsp. obovatum
entry.content: This shrub had finished flowering but the remnants of the flowers made a beautiful spectacle.

entry.title: Grevillea steiglitziana
entry.content: Young plant on the road edge

entry.title: Phyllanthus hirtellus
entry.content: Many of the plants had been foraged heavily.

entry.title: Acacia aspera subsp. parviceps
entry.content: Area had been cleared - plants developing into substantial shrubs and flowering very well.

entry.title: Pultenaea daltonii
entry.content: Plants growing among other shrubs have some protection for the herbivores allowing for more leaves and healthier plants.

entry.title: Pultenaea daltonii
entry.content: Many plants in the area have been heavily foraged and some have almost no leaves left.

entry.title: Grevillea chrysophaea
entry.content: Very small plant but still producing a flower

entry.title: Bossiaea obcordata
entry.content: First flower I have seen this season - plants are carrying lots of buds.

entry.title: Olearia minor
entry.content: This plant had a caterpillar which was feeding on the flower.

entry.title: Boronia anemonifolia subsp. anemonifolia
entry.content: The four or five plants found were very small having been eaten by herbivores (rabbits, wallabies or both) extensively.

entry.title: Hibbertia exutiacies
entry.content: Small shrub - all plants have been heavily grazed. These plants have the propensity to grow amongst the mosses.

entry.title: Grevillea steiglitziana
entry.content: This grevillea is a low spreading shrub with shiny, lightly toothed, holly-like leaves and bright red toothbrush flowers. It is found in Victoria, mostly confined to the Brisbane Ranges between Geelong & Bacchus marsh. Grows in dry, open eucalypt forest
